    <Descriptive_Notes>
      <Descriptive_Note>
        <Note_Text>Wood of the species Betula alleghaniensis, native to the northeastern part of North America, with light yellow sapwood and reddish-brown heartwood. It is similar to sweet birch and is not separated from it commercially. It is used in the making of fine furniture, joinery, spools, bobbins, and plywood.</Note_Text>
        <Note_Language>English</Note_Language>
